# Kinematics: The Study of Motion

:::objective
By the end of this chapter the student will be able to:
- Distinguish between position, displacement, and distance traveled.
- Calculate average and instantaneous velocity.
- Solve URM and UARM problems.
- Apply the free-fall equations.
- Interpret position-time and velocity-time graphs.
:::

---

## 1. Position and displacement

**Kinematics** is the branch of mechanics that describes the motion of bodies without considering the forces that produce it. To describe motion we need to define a reference frame.

:::definition id="def-position"
**Position** | Coordinate that indicates the location of an object relative to a reference point (origin) at a given instant. It is a vector quantity represented as m{x(t)} in one dimension.
:::

:::definition id="def-displacement"
**Displacement** | Change in the position of an object: m{Δx = x_f − x_i}. It is a vector from the initial point to the final point, independent of the path taken.
:::

:::warning
Do not confuse **displacement** with **distance traveled**. Displacement is a vector (has direction and can be negative); distance is a scalar (always positive). A runner who completes one lap of a 400 m track has distance traveled = 400 m but displacement = 0.
:::

:::diagram id="fig-displacement" title="Displacement vs. distance traveled"
Number line (x-axis) representation:
- Point A at m{x = 2 m} (initial position)
- Point B at m{x = 8 m} (intermediate position)
- Point C at m{x = 5 m} (final position)
- Path: A → B → C
- Displacement: straight arrow from A to C (m{Δx = 3 m})
- Distance traveled: m{6 m + 3 m = 9 m}

```mermaid
graph LR
    A["A (x=2m)"] -->|"6 m"| B["B (x=8m)"]
    B -->|"3 m"| C["C (x=5m)"]
    A -. "Δx = 3 m" .-> C
```
:::

---

## 2. Velocity

:::definition id="def-avg-velocity"
**Average velocity** | Ratio of displacement to time interval: m{v̄ = Δx/Δt}. It is a vector quantity. SI units are m/s.
:::

:::definition id="def-inst-velocity"
**Instantaneous velocity** | Limit of average velocity as the time interval approaches zero: m{v = lim(Δt→0) Δx/Δt = dx/dt}. It corresponds to the slope of the position-time curve at each instant.
:::

:::key-concept id="slope-xt"
In a position vs. time graph, the **slope** of the curve at any point is the instantaneous velocity. A straight line indicates constant velocity; a curve indicates acceleration.
:::

:::example title="Average velocity calculation"
A cyclist starts at position m{x₁ = 2 km} at m{t₁ = 0 min} and arrives at m{x₂ = 14 km} at m{t₂ = 30 min}.

:::math
v̄ = Δx/Δt = (14 − 2)/(30 − 0) km/min = 12/30 = 0.4 km/min = 24 km/h
:::
:::

:::history title="Galileo and the measurement of motion" characters="Galileo Galilei" year="1604"
In 17th-century Italy there were no precise chronometers. Galileo needed to measure time accurately to study falling bodies, but the clocks of his era were too imprecise.

His solution was ingenious: instead of dropping objects vertically (too fast to measure), he built polished inclined planes to "dilute" gravity. He used a water container with a small hole — the water that flowed out during the fall was weighed, and the weight was proportional to the elapsed time.

With this rudimentary method he demonstrated that the distance covered in free fall is proportional to the square of the time (m{d ∝ t²}), one of the first quantitative laws of physics and the foundation of modern kinematics.
:::

---

## 3. Acceleration

:::definition id="def-acceleration"
**Acceleration** | Rate of change of velocity with respect to time: m{a = Δv/Δt}. Measured in m/s² in SI. It can be positive (speeding up), negative (slowing down), or zero (constant velocity).
:::

:::note
In everyday language "accelerate" means to go faster. In physics, a negative acceleration does not necessarily mean braking — it depends on the direction of motion. An object moving to the left and accelerating to the left has negative velocity and negative acceleration, but its speed increases.
:::

---

## 4. Uniform Rectilinear Motion (URM)

:::key-concept id="urm"
In URM, velocity is constant (m{a = 0}). Position varies linearly with time:

:::math
x = x₀ + v·t
:::
:::

:::comparison title="URM vs. UARM"
| Property | URM | UARM |
|---|---|---|
| Velocity | Constant | Changes uniformly |
| Acceleration | 0 | Constant (≠ 0) |
| x-t graph | Straight line | Parabola |
| v-t graph | Horizontal line | Inclined line |
| Position equation | m{x = x₀ + v·t} | m{x = x₀ + v₀·t + ½·a·t²} |
:::

:::diagram id="fig-vt-urm-uarm" title="v-t graphs for URM and UARM"
Two velocity vs. time graphs side by side. The left one shows URM (horizontal line at constant velocity). The right one shows UARM (inclined straight line starting from v₀ with slope equal to acceleration). In both, the shaded area under the curve represents displacement.

```svg
<svg viewBox="0 0 520 200" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
  <!-- URM -->
  <text x="120" y="18" text-anchor="middle" font-size="13" font-weight="600" fill="currentColor">URM</text>
  <line x1="40" y1="170" x2="230" y2="170" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
  <line x1="40" y1="170" x2="40" y2="25" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
  <text x="135" y="192" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="currentColor">t (s)</text>
  <text x="18" y="100" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="currentColor" transform="rotate(-90,18,100)">v (m/s)</text>
  <rect x="40" y="70" width="180" height="100" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.08"/>
  <line x1="40" y1="70" x2="220" y2="70" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"/>
  <text x="225" y="74" font-size="11" fill="currentColor">v</text>
  <text x="115" y="130" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.5">Δx = v · t</text>
  <!-- UARM -->
  <text x="400" y="18" text-anchor="middle" font-size="13" font-weight="600" fill="currentColor">UARM</text>
  <line x1="300" y1="170" x2="500" y2="170" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
  <line x1="300" y1="170" x2="300" y2="25" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
  <text x="400" y="192" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="currentColor">t (s)</text>
  <text x="278" y="100" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="currentColor" transform="rotate(-90,278,100)">v (m/s)</text>
  <polygon points="300,170 300,130 490,40 490,170" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.08"/>
  <line x1="300" y1="130" x2="490" y2="40" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"/>
  <text x="285" y="134" text-anchor="end" font-size="10" fill="currentColor">v₀</text>
  <text x="495" y="44" font-size="11" fill="currentColor">v</text>
  <text x="395" y="140" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.5">slope = a</text>
</svg>
```
:::

---

## 5. Uniformly Accelerated Rectilinear Motion (UARM)

The UARM equations are:

:::math
v = v₀ + a·t
x = x₀ + v₀·t + ½·a·t²
v² = v₀² + 2·a·(x − x₀)
:::

:::mnemonic
**The 3 UARM equations — each one omits a variable:**
- Equation 1 omits **position** (m{x} does not appear)
- Equation 2 omits **final velocity** (m{v} does not appear)
- Equation 3 omits **time** (m{t} does not appear)

Trick: identify what data you are missing in the problem and use the equation that does not need it.
:::

:::exercise id="ex-uarm-01" title="Braking a car"
A car travels at 90 km/h when the driver brakes uniformly and stops in 5 seconds. Calculate:
a) The braking acceleration.
b) The distance covered during braking.

:::solution
Data: m{v₀ = 90 km/h = 25 m/s}, m{v = 0 m/s}, m{t = 5 s}

a) m{a = (v − v₀)/t = (0 − 25)/5 = −5 m/s²}

b) m{x = v₀·t + ½·a·t² = 25·5 + ½·(−5)·5² = 125 − 62.5 = 62.5 m}
:::
:::

:::application title="Braking distance in road safety"
Braking distance is critical in traffic engineering. At 90 km/h, the car in the example needs 62.5 m to stop — not counting the driver's reaction time (≈ 1 s), which adds another 25 m. The total stopping distance would be ~87.5 m. This calculation determines the minimum following distance between vehicles and the length of braking zones on highways.
:::

---

## 6. Free fall

:::key-concept id="free-fall"
Free fall is a special case of UARM where the acceleration is gravity:

:::math
a = g ≈ 9.8 m/s²
:::

In the absence of air resistance, all bodies fall with the same acceleration regardless of their mass.
:::

:::aside title="Did you know?"
In 1971, astronaut David Scott simultaneously dropped a hammer and a feather on the Moon (no atmosphere). Both reached the ground at exactly the same time, confirming Galileo's prediction 367 years later — but this time on another world.
:::

:::exercise id="ex-fall-01" title="Object falling from a building"
A ball is dropped from the roof of a 45 m tall building (m{v₀ = 0}). Calculate:
a) The time it takes to reach the ground.
b) The impact velocity.
(Use m{g = 10 m/s²} for simplicity)

:::solution
Data: m{y₀ = 45 m}, m{v₀ = 0}, m{a = g = 10 m/s²}

a) m{y = ½·g·t²} → m{45 = ½·10·t²} → m{t² = 9} → **t = 3 s**

b) m{v = g·t = 10·3 = 30 m/s} (108 km/h)
:::
:::

:::diagram id="fig-free-fall" title="Successive positions in free fall"
Vertical diagram showing an object in free fall:
- Vertical axis with marks every second (m{t = 0, 1, 2, 3 s})
- Object positions: 0 m, 5 m, 20 m, 45 m
- Increasing distances between positions (5 m, 15 m, 25 m)
- Illustrates visually that separation between positions grows with time

```mermaid
graph TD
    T0["t=0s | y=0m | v=0 m/s"] -->|"5 m"| T1["t=1s | y=5m | v=10 m/s"]
    T1 -->|"15 m"| T2["t=2s | y=20m | v=20 m/s"]
    T2 -->|"25 m"| T3["t=3s | y=45m | v=30 m/s"]
```
:::

:::image id="fig-galileo-tower"
file: galileo_pisa.jpg
title: "Galileo's thought experiment at the Tower of Pisa"
description: "Classic depiction of Galileo's experiment: two spheres of different mass dropped simultaneously from a height. Although there is no historical evidence that Galileo actually performed this experiment at the Tower of Pisa, the thought experiment was fundamental to his refutation of Aristotelian physics."
