## 7. Interpreting graphs

:::key-concept id="graphs-kinematics"
Graphs are fundamental tools in kinematics:
- In an **x vs. t** graph: the slope is velocity; curvature indicates acceleration.
- In a **v vs. t** graph: the slope is acceleration; the area under the curve is displacement.
:::

:::diagram id="fig-xva-relationship" title="Relationship between position, velocity, and acceleration"
Diagram showing the three kinematic quantities (position, velocity, acceleration) and the mathematical operations connecting them: differentiate to go from position to velocity and from velocity to acceleration; integrate in the reverse direction.

```d2
x: Position x(t) {
  shape: rectangle
}
v: Velocity v(t) {
  shape: rectangle
}
a: Acceleration a(t) {
  shape: rectangle
}

x -> v: dx/dt (derivative) {
  style.stroke-dash: 0
}
v -> a: dv/dt (derivative) {
  style.stroke-dash: 0
}
a -> v: ∫a·dt (integral) {
  style.stroke-dash: 3
}
v -> x: ∫v·dt (integral) {
  style.stroke-dash: 3
}
```
:::

:::diagram id="fig-problem-solving" title="Kinematics problem-solving flowchart"
Flowchart for solving kinematics problems: identify the type of motion (URM or UARM), list knowns and unknowns, select the appropriate equation, solve, and verify units and sign.

```dot
digraph {
  rankdir=TB
  node [shape=box, style=rounded]

  start [label="Read the problem", shape=ellipse]
  identify [label="Identify motion type\n(URM or UARM)"]
  list [label="List knowns\nand unknowns"]
  select [label="Select equation\n(omits the unknown\nyou don't need)"]
  solve [label="Solve algebraically\nthen substitute"]
  check [label="Check units\nand sign"]
  done [label="Answer", shape=ellipse]

  start -> identify -> list -> select -> solve -> check -> done
}
```
:::

:::teacher-only
**Note for the instructor:** This is a good moment for a hands-on activity with motion sensors or smartphone apps that record position and velocity. Students can walk in front of the sensor and see their graphs in real time, reinforcing the connection between physical movement and mathematical representation.

Assessment suggestion: give students a v-t graph and ask them to:
1. Calculate the acceleration in each segment
2. Draw the corresponding x-t graph
3. Calculate the total displacement (area under the curve)
:::

:::student-only
Practice drawing x-t and v-t graphs for the following motions:
1. A car that starts from rest and accelerates uniformly for 10 s.
2. A car that travels at constant speed and then brakes to a stop.
3. A ball thrown upward that rises, stops, and falls.
:::

---

:::summary
- **Position** is the location of an object relative to the origin; **displacement** is the change in position (m{Δx}, vector); **distance** is the total path length (scalar).
- **Average velocity** is m{v̄ = Δx/Δt}; **instantaneous velocity** is the derivative m{dx/dt} (slope in x-t graph).
- **Acceleration** is the rate of change of velocity (m{a = Δv/Δt}).
- In **URM**: m{v = const}, m{x = x₀ + v·t}.
- In **UARM**: m{a = const}, with three fundamental equations relating m{x}, m{v}, m{a}, and m{t}.
- **Free fall** is UARM with m{a = g ≈ 9.8 m/s²}. All bodies fall equally without air resistance.
- x-t and v-t graphs contain all kinematic information: slopes and areas reveal velocity, acceleration, and displacement.
:::

---

:::question type="open" id="q-train"
1. A train starts from rest and accelerates at m{2 m/s²} for 20 s. It then maintains constant speed for 60 s. Finally, it brakes uniformly and stops in 10 s. Calculate the total distance traveled.
2. Explain why braking distance quadruples when speed doubles.

= 1. Phase 1: m{x = ½·2·20² = 400 m} (m{v_f = 40 m/s}). Phase 2: m{x = 40·60 = 2400 m}. Phase 3: m{x = 40·10 + ½·(−4)·10² = 200 m}. Total = 3000 m.
= 2. Because braking distance depends on m{v²} (from the equation m{v² = v₀² + 2·a·d}). If m{v} doubles, m{v²} quadruples, and with the same deceleration the distance quadruples.
:::

:::question type="choice" id="q-highest-point"
An object is thrown vertically upward. At the highest point of its trajectory:

~ Both velocity and acceleration are zero # Gravitational acceleration never vanishes
= Velocity is zero and acceleration is m{g} (downward) # Correct — velocity is momentarily zero but gravity keeps acting
~ Velocity is maximum and acceleration is zero # Velocity is maximum at launch, not at the highest point
~ Both velocity and acceleration are maximum # Both cannot be maximum simultaneously in this case
:::

:::question type="choice" id="q-vt-graph"
In a velocity vs. time graph, displacement is obtained by calculating:

~ The slope of the curve # The slope gives acceleration, not displacement
~ The y-intercept # That gives the initial velocity
~ The maximum velocity # That is just a single value
= The area under the curve # Correct — the integral of m{v(t)} is displacement
:::

:::question type="true-false" id="q-free-fall-mass"
In the absence of air resistance, a heavier object falls faster than a lighter one.

= false # Incorrect — all objects fall with the same acceleration regardless of mass. Galileo demonstrated this in the 17th century.
:::

:::question type="case" id="q-forensics"
A traffic forensics expert arrives at an accident scene. The skid marks on the asphalt measure 40 m. The friction coefficient between tires and dry asphalt is m{μ = 0.7} (deceleration m{≈ 6.86 m/s²}). The speed limit in that area is 60 km/h.

a) At what speed was the vehicle traveling before braking?
b) Was it exceeding the speed limit?
c) If the pavement were wet (m{μ = 0.4}, deceleration m{≈ 3.92 m/s²}), how long would the skid mark be at the same initial speed?

= a) m{v = √(2 × 6.86 × 40) = 23.4 m/s = 84.3 km/h}
= b) Yes, exceeding the limit by 24.3 km/h (84.3 vs 60 km/h)
= c) m{d = v²/(2·a) = 23.4²/(2 × 3.92) = 69.9 m} — nearly double than on dry road
:::

